s and '70s. In this beautifully written, meticulously researched book, Elizabeth Abel assembles a variegated archive of segregation signs and photographs that translated a set of regional practices into a national conversation about race. Abel also brilliantly investigates the semiotic system through which segregation worked to reveal how the signs functioned in particular spaces and contexts that shifted the grounds of race from the somatic to the social sphere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxSegregationxHistoryx20th centuryxSouthern States. 0aAfrican AmericansxSegregationzSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectsxHistoryx20th centuryxSouthern States. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aRacism in popular culturexHistoryx20th centuryxSouthern States. 0aRacism in popular culturezSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aSigns and signboardsxHistoryx20th centuryxSouthern States. 0aSigns and signboardszSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aVisual communicationxHistoryx20th centuryxSouthern States. 0aVisual communicationzSouthern StatesxHistoryy20th century. 7aHISTORY / United States / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package 2000-2015z978311066334108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311069042240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520945869423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780520945869.jpg  a978-3-11-066334-1  UC Press eBook Package 2000-2015c2000d2015  a978-3-11-069042-2  UC Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles